The initial actions taken to investigate or inspect the event were:
* Telephone contact with the principal medical facility serving the five communities described above showed that office and emergency-room visits for gastrointestinal disease had risen sharply March 6-11;
* Review of emergency room records showed that the increase was entirely in residents of Eagle-Vail and Avon, not of Vail itself or the other two communities in the service area of the medical facility;
* Household telephone survey was performed on March 13 and 14 by calling every 6th listed residential number in that exchange until 48 households were reached; about 80 households in the sample did not answer on multiple attempts in a 24-hour period, and 20 were disconnected.

The following steps were taken to restore the system after some time passed:
\begin{itemize}
\item Rigorous disposal of patients' faeces
\item Chlorination of piped water
\item Boiling or treatment of drinking water.
\end{itemize}

The investigation included:

1. House-to-house hygiene education through 161,370 meetings with families in affected communities;
2. Periodic water samples for cholera testing;
3. Chlorination of 86,832 shallow wells in residential areas;
4. House-to-house distribution of 1,139,694 chlorine tablets and liquid chlorine in the areas most affected by the outbreak;
5. House-to-house distribution of 98,000 ORS packets;
6. Information, education and communication campaigns on personal hygiene and use of ORS for the Kabul residents most affected, including distribution of 42,000 posters, 60,000 leaflets, 400 flipcharts and 200 banners.

The immediate actions taken to mitigate the effects of contamination were:

1. House-to-house hygiene education through 161,370 meetings with families in affected communities;
